The paper deals with information theory and communication channels, which are typically covered in the sub-categories of cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.ITP (Information Theory and Probability). The paper also discusses the evaluation of the sum rate, which is related to network information theory, covered in cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). The randomized time-division strategy mentioned in the abstract is a form of algorithm, which falls under the sub-category of cs.CC (Computational Complexity). Finally, the paper deals with inequalities and bounds, which are covered in the sub-category of cs.SI (Systems and Control).
